15-08:ADMIN: PM: Andrea the second->Randomonioum : Introduction to genetics: The newest genetic machines divide genes into 14 blocks of 3 hexadecimal figures numbers. Each of these blocks is composed by a sequence of genes which controls a set of enzymes which in turn have an effect on specific functions of the body. What exactly those functions are for each block is currently unknown, except for block 14 which is the sum of genes which make us different from monkeys. The new genetic analyzer is a tool which allows to find and recognize the enzymes produced by cells through blood analysis. The DNA modifier allows to modify each block individually through the use of radiation; heavy radiation may cause random mutations in the test subject.

15-08:ADMIN: PM: Andrea the second->Randomonioum : The new human genome project: The New Human Genome Project, which takes its name from an old 20th century project, has as its goal to understand how the newly found DNA "blocks" work, what are their functions and, by this, find cures to various genetic illnesses. Some other goals may be genetic alteration to create improved humans, even though probability of such a mutation is very low and considered ethically and morally wrong. Experiments will work following the same procedure: modify a block with the DNA modifier until it reaches an high value, which means that the genes are activated, then analyze the patient with a genetic analyzer to find what enzymes are being produced and what the function of those enzymes is. This simple procedure, only possible due to the world's most advanced genetic machines. will allow quick identification of the function of the blocks, allowing breakthroughs in genetic science to happen in the following months, instead of the tens of years previously thought.
